At the end of the trade, the Prague Stock Exchange fell into a negative
After this morning's sharp collapse, Prague Stock Exchange corrected the losses.
Transactions in CEZ shares reached almost half of the daily business.
The Prague Stock Exchange has followed up on its Monday slump since the start of Tuesday’s trade, when it fell by almost 6 percent.
This time, the fall in shares on Wall Street is behind the fall.
In our country, too, the market's response to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
The Fall of Shares in Asia
The dramatic fall on Tuesday was experienced by stock exchanges in Asia, although the indexes eventually erased some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng Exchange index in Hong Kong wrote off almost four percent during trade, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to around 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stock on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, has fallen by 3.8 percent, and in Shanghai the markets have been closed.
Sydney Stocks lost more than five percent, but eventually lost 4.3 percent.
The Taiwanese stock market, according to its index, has fallen by 3.6 percent.
"The timing of a rescue operation in the US is uncertain and it will affect financial markets around the world," said Chief of Hong Kong Monetary Office Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines monetary policy separately, i.e. without dependence on China’s central bank.
Hong Kong’s interest rates are at the same level as the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly return to negotiations and approve the proposal for support for the financial system.
Otherwise, they say there is a risk that other countries will feel the effects.
American Stock Blood Bath
On Monday, the American House of Representatives rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was to spend up to $700 billion (almost CZK 12 trillion).
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indexes recorded the biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index has dropped by almost seven percent, and the drop to a similar extent was the last recorded in 1987.
The index was falling before the vote, but once it became clear that the proposal had failed in the House, the index was in free fall.
Congress retreated: The US government can pump $700 billion into banks
US Congress leaders and President George W. Bush’s government have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the American financial system.
The vote on it will be at the beginning of next week.
American legislators have made a breakthrough in talks about approving a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance for the US financial system of $700 billion (approximately CZK 12 trillion).
But it is not yet won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final draft of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed at the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services of the House Barney Frank told Reuters.
According to sources, the Senate could probably vote on the plan first on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first major psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
However, there will then be a "s sobering" thanks to the complexity of the mechanisms by which to help markets achieve even in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences about what the form of the market stabilisation package is supposed to look like," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi to the Bloomberg agency.
According to her, the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with US finance minister Henry Paulson on Sunday to give a definitive form to the government fund.
This should buy unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which are pulling financial firms into heavy losses and threatening the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement of a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
We still need to continue our recovery plan, but I think we are there," said Paulson.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is affecting stock markets that are falling sharply.
According to Nevada's democratic senator Harry Reid, the legislators are trying to reach a definitive agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone, where Congress's decision could affect Monday's trading.
However, it is not yet clear, for certain, when both chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, nor whether the negotiations at the last moment can be stuck on a problem.
Lawmakers hope to be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will admit a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be available as soon as possible, as President George Bush requested.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program does not perform its function, in the sequence of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush appreciated progress in the negotiations
While the President may veto this decision, Congress may overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to raise funds for the purchase of bad mortgage securities, whose value had fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to repay their mortgages, remained preserved.
"We've worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
American President Bush is also satisfied with the progress of the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said that Bush is satisfied with Saturday's progress and appreciates the "both-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economies".
Limitations on golden parachutes
Senate Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said that the legislators agreed on responsibility for the money program, protection of taxpayers from losses, closure of concessions, timing of financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called gold parachutes for directors of the company participating in the programme and set up a committee to supervise the fund.
That should be run by the Treasury Department.
"We have worked very hard on this and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be useful to the market for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new mortgage payments that it buys in order to reduce the monthly repayment costs for debtors and allow them to keep their houses.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to chief economist Patrio Finance David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"That is because it is not known what mechanism and at what price the troubled assets will be redeemed.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government will divide their losses," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
If the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week, Mark says it's not that important.
"It is much more important that this week the Congressmen agree to support this plan and to sanctify it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on approval is the most important thing at the moment," Marek emphasized.
Knife blade fight: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We'll advise on how to choose
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
From that it seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Still, there are enough reasons to buy a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the manner of use and the demands of the future owner.
It's hard to get home a high-end expensive record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
For one thing, such music products on LP boards do not come out and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if your vinyl shelves contain art rock, jazz or blues, you may at least dream of such a gramophone.
It is the same with music on the road, i.e. music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
It may be unacceptable for some to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may hardly bite the headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life also determines
Some top music players can do much more than just play music, but what most cell phones can't do.
No modern device is as universal as a phone.
Besides primary functions, phone calls and text messages, he can play music and video, record both, have a better one, the worse one, and maybe even navigate.
And considering smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can photograph anything.
The versatility of a cell phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the display indicator sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few phones can play music for more than 10 12 hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap phones, therefore, count on them not to play for more than a few hours.
If you make any more calls here and there, get one more charger at work just to be sure - that's also true for more expensive devices.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the worse will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation per charge.
Another problem arises when you record music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the device has a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on a memory card, but few card readers can handle miniature memory cards that are used in mobile phones without reduction.
You don't need any special software for players except for exceptions (iPod).
Just fill the device with USB music from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players already create a music library by the name of the performer, album title, genre or user evaluation.
Some devices only display the tree structure of directories like the Explorer in Windows and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones are more capable
When selecting a specific device, you should especially care about battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and of course also about the comfort of the control.
If music is primarily a set and if you listen to it every day just briefly on the tram, you just need any cell phone that plays MP3.
Which almost any cell phone can do.
You don't even have to watch too much of what music formats a cell phone or player can do.
MP3 can handle all and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and besides it, the vast majority of the instruments can also handle music in WMA format.
AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods) is less frequent.
Better mobile phones also allow for example buying music online.
Just visit the respective website of the operator (or another provider) via mobile Internet and buy a song or album.
This service could already in itself be a strong argument for the acquisition of a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to fast-fermented radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this method of selling music (either through GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) is dominated by the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones around all the time.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you feel the phone in your pocket while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends whether you always carry headphones or at least wire handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker that has almost every cell phone, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the greatest advantage of music cell phones will be the prize for many.
The cheapest ones are normally under three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns, you'll already have a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the absence of output to common headphones.
The best and technically the most equipped phones even with a 3.5 mm socket for common headphones cost up to 15,000.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy to operate.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can really control everyone.
Minimum functions, similarity of control with a previously common tape recorder or perhaps a gramophone is obvious.
There is no collision in the form of an accidentally turned on mobile Internet and subsequently a giant data transfer account.
What kind of device to reach for?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchange memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card you can fit into 2,000 crowns.
Be careful, though.
For basic models only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
According to capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 CZK.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, reach for specialized phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokies and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the operator comfort is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
The farthest is in Sony Ericsson, whose walkman cell phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand CZK, but with more memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours), will take MP3 players away from the above brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services such as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet we're missing something here - a virtual operator who would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
After all, CTÚ confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps taken by the European Commission in the area of roaming charges regulation, the paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into a fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetrations over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to play on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classic operator with his own network probably doesn't have much chance (after all, it would probably be hard to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought significant price reductions, to which even classical operators had to respond.
Even before the entry of a pike such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the start of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even a bet on a fresh target group can be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Administrative men vote Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if a similar concept as in Poland could be followed by us.
The spokesperson for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts about this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, Spokeswoman of the financial group Penta, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not in favour of this idea.
Rather the opposite, they try to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitor from being created.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the GTS Novera Group, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only solid, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them in the negotiations," says the group press spokesperson Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe it's time for a better time, then.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to maybe the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Srsen, of the O2 Telefónics Press Department, said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Press spokesperson for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2: "We have not yet noticed any viable and mutually advantageous business project on which to build further."
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it's hard for any virtual operator to appear.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to be able to think in this short term."
Vodafone pays attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider most beneficial from the point of view of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The process of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a fall in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when operators care about something, they are able to pull together is also evidenced by the movements around the formation of U:fona.
Probably the biggest pressure towards CTÚ went at the time of the creation of U:fona from the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
But now U:fon is useful as an argument why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would impose high demands on him and above all on his services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, it is directly striking the total lack of interest of Czech regulators.
This is not just about the Czech Technical University's position, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries - has no power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stand on the issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to rent the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS External Relations Department said in response to our inquiry.
It may not surprise the representatives of the operators of such a worded statement.
From an office to represent consumers' interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market, it is more than considered.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices for mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not part of the interests of the Authority.
In fact, the whole case is shockingly touchingly matched by the three mobile operators that result from their reactions.
The question, if this is really just a coincidence, is offered entirely by itself.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly only a result of chance and a hard competitive struggle.
"The Authority did not find signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the CTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - it is always necessary to agree with the network operator to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on his network.
So in a certain segment, it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to ÚOHS that three mobile operators are doing similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the said GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
Assessing responsibility on the CTU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which the ÚOHS keeps away from the whole matter.
We've already met him in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the CTU's powers to competition in telecommunications has failed, although many experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the OHS must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's okay when no one's watching.
However, the operation of pseudovirtual operators, several of which exist in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own mobile phone service prices, but which are only partially public.
They are usually multilevel marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The prices of these companies usually come only to the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company acts as a classic company customer with a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer then gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar sales.
"If there are cases you are talking about, this could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová answered.
However, it is highly unlikely that such activities would not reach responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are prevented from doing so.
In fact, the activities of these companies have considerable profits and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law of such speculation allows, however, the services of these companies use only a negligible percentage of customers.
Moreover, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not kept in their name, so they cannot have it fully as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that's what the CTU should be at least weird.
In addition, another question is open for the OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to similar procedures, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the OHS has relatively strong powers to detect similar activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the operators’ explanation that they have no idea of any such activity and their business conditions forbid it.
When We Won't Be Most Precious
As has been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought down prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to defend their creation more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these moments that regulators intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, and others were packing on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are switching the whole case like a hot potato.
From our experience, we can't shake the impression that the lack of clarity in their competence is more than useful to them in these cases.
But let's not blow our brains out.
If the backroom information is correct and the virtual operator really appears in our country soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If any of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will hardly be possible for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling out more than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of Czech State Day festively introduced new recordings of the state anthem Where my home is.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the leadership of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choir version and instrumental version.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took the singing.
The authors of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Belohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymens.
He had already told Czech Radio that he deliberately chose singers with young representative voices that are prominent and popular to sing solo variations.
"From the beginning, I tried to be careful with both of them and then with the congregation to have a clear diction, so that the text could be understood so as to be compatible," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate the 175th anniversary next year.
Song Where my home sounded for the first time in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theatre in the original Czech game Fidlovačka Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by music by František Škroup.
She gained popularity, and people spontaneously took her for their own.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem.
One of the seven state symbols remained after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
