Prague public transport on Wednesday for the first time on a chip
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will enter the metro, tram and bus station, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At this point, it can be purchased by roughly 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will apply from 1 January 2009) and also have their chip card uploaded to the infocentres and workplaces of the Transport enterprise in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can also be purchased on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz from yesterday.
Over 400 customers took advantage of the service until afternoon hours.
Those who start using the Internet shop can definitely forget about the window at the metro stations, where they have had to stand regularly in long queues on paper tickets.
The coupon will be purchased via the Internet and uploaded to the Opencard card in one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"At these places, the passenger desk with a trained staff is available to help interested customers with online purchases and also uploads a coupon on their card," said the spokesperson for the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons to Opencard also in self-service slot machines, which are installed in several subway vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, they resemble ticket marks, and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltava.
"Now there are five in the city, but there should be eighty by the end of the year," he added.
Coupon checks the driver's seat slot
The vending machines that start working tomorrow are simple.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip into it and the coupon previously paid will upload itself to it.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow apply not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
Thus on suburban trains and bus lines with the number 300 to 499, which are used mainly by the inhabitants of Central Bohemia.
"On trains included in the Prague Integrated Transport, conductors are equipped with card readers, using them to determine the time and band validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal, of Ropid organization, which sets timetables for Prague public transport.
The suburban buses have card readers built in the driver's box office.
When entering, it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver, but it is also necessary to attach Opencard to the designated location on the side of the cash register.
This will check the validity of the recorded coupons.
"If passengers need to verify the validity of recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take suburban buses and do not remember when the coupon expires can go back to self-service slot machines where coupons are recorded.
Here, information about the validity of their documents will be displayed on the instrument display.
The Sudetens wanted a referendum from the US
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans requested the inclusion of Shumava with the United States.
It comes from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America at least.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans reportedly turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is reflected, among other things, in a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov are asking in a letter from the American President not to allow the "Shumava County" - taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement - to return to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want to be sure that American troops come into German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says the letter, signed by the words "The people whose fate lies in Šumava's heart".
Since joining Czechoslovakia allegedly gives Sudeten Germans - in knowledge of Czech national nature - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of a letter from the US President to take over the Protectorate for the present and eternal times.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million people, you would admit this territory to a foreign country that oppresses and disproves minorities and nothing, has contributed nothing to the Allies' victory," says the letter.
