When a rat or a cockroach escapes danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that even many animals have feelings.
But how could it be verified that they feel the same way when they behave like we do?
For several years, the Web magazine "Edge" has published contributions from well-known scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in her series presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it, when we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we begin to engage in another kind and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter into an impassable terrain because hardware does not match.
When a rat comes into danger, he does what many other animals do: pretend to be dead, flee, or attack.
People behave in a similar way, some scientists conclude that there is a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe in that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal life.
This is because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include side prefrontal cortex (because of its share in short-term memory and performance or control functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least with those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could hide the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his perception is associated with the language, it is often said that consciousness depends on him.
In this case, we could rule out animals.
But even if language consciousness did not matter, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, however designed, would probably differ from most of our states of consciousness.
That's why it's hard to figure out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is not possible to measure even, because of special hardware, to analyze it based on our own experience, it puts us at the forefront of great problems.
Most of my outlets relate to the content of conscious experience, but besides that, there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically more accessible.
It would be possible to examine animal consciousness processes regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in short-term memory studies in primates, especially in visualization.
But this approach, addressed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlations of consciousness rather than on causal mechanisms: they can both be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the importance of a non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I conclude that an emotional system, such as a fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defence system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) utilizes the memory.
Seen from this angle, the feelings are closely linked to those areas of the cortex, which are characterized by primates, and especially by humans.
In connection with language nature, there is a subtle degree of variation of perception, because by using words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states to attribute them to others.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of Cortex and the brain stem devoted to physical feelings, like Jaak Pankseep, which, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily participate in feelings perceived by several animal families.
In theory, I cannot resist this, but I find it inconclusive.
Pankseep argues that what seems like fear to us in rats and humans probably feels the same way: But how can it be verified, does Pankseep also say whether rats and humans feel the same way when they behave similarly?
Does the cockroach flee from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, mere similarity cannot prove the congruency of the experience.
True, the neural comparison moves us on: rats and humans have similar brain strains, but cockroaches and brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it were possible to prove it in humans: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to examine emotional behavior rather than emotional perception of rats.
In any case, in this case, we can look forward to progress on the neural level if we measure the same for rats and humans.
Just as I don't study the language and consciousness of rats, I don't study the feelings, I don't know if they exist.
