Proudness and obstacles to the lives of black people in a separate city
Hidden among the vast amusement parks of the Greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy, and huge, lies a quiet city in which the pride and demands of African-American life come to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courses, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough guava, two schools and no prison."
Now it's a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville festival Zora! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a party, even though she made it a stop for tourists by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in the year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on races, many of the locals remain cautious about the looks of strangers.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of the black rise and a community of almost 2400 people, where the poverty rate is double the national average.
It is the center of literature, but also oaks, shielded by an example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that came from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons call it.
She introduced her hometown to the world through hearty books full of dialects like "Mules and Men (Muly and Men)" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida tourist guide changed the city a bit into Route 17, which leads through the frequently ephemeral center of Florida, into the stage of black history and human drama.
With the big drum in her life and literature, Hurston introduced her readers to the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of every kind and anything that fits into an hour hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville connected with self-government, but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Obviously, this wasn't a typical Fodor's publishing house.
Actually, it wasn't a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls' choirs, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chipper eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Florida's Jacksonville.
Seventy - seven - year - old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of the time, when she came into town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevy, smoked, and wore pants in the city, which is still proud of dignified clothing.
Most of the residents were fascinated, said Franklin, but many scoffed.
"The people of Zoru have always been happy to see," Franklin said.
But, he added, rocking a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
It seemed like Eatonville had forgotten about her and the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920 ’ s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived.
There were no major funeral ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood its significance for the world or its legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's biography, "wrapped in Rainbows", published in 2003.
Change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to drag the city through the five-way highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-way main road.
The discovery of Orlando has already pushed Interstate Highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, has ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950 ’ s, the struggle to mix races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and things at people who sat on the side," said Franklin.
"In fact, we had a lady who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In her letter to The Orlando Sentinel of 1955, Hurston questioned the request of the Supreme Court for forced integration and declared his decision in the Brown case against the Education Chamber "to my race rather than to celebrate."
The inhabitants now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
"Black children were used to hugs - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You are not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there is a cultural barrier," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights helped create space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker reached Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to revive her reputation.
Five years later, he came to the shelves at the bookstores, praised by Robert E. Hemenway's résumé of Hurston, who put her back in the U.S. Canon.
The highway project arrived just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville found the ramp lights again.
The former Hurston neighbors now viewed her as a savior.
To show what could happen to his highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"The five streams of highways have resurrected, you'd say it's detonated, real civic pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd said it more simply, "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
The extra-urban like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the church in 1993, began to appear in more numbers, and the inhabitants began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new single-story library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 at the re-esphalted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act like a lost alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today is 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come looking for the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated cautiously.
Permission for most interviews is required to have certain things in advance - like murals in the oldest eatonville church, painted by white people and displayed by black people in fields - not to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Jones, a courageous, confident teacher who likes to be richly red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival grew, domestic pride also increased.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, an 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, sincere love of the community sounds when he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or the police, who he says could use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11 - year - old twins of Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass through here, think, 'Well, this town is nothing compared to the others,' said Alondra Kenon recently after church on Sunday.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a while, it's a very nice town."
Here in New York, we're all fluent in finance.
At first glance, nothing has changed here.
If tourists in Manhattan were to stay away from newsstands and giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the glass bee hive offices above their heads every day, bankers and investment fund managers monopolizing New York have the worst "bad day in office" since the 1929 crisis.
Messengers still rumble with metal carts on the sidewalks and transfer muffin pans to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics keep moving between towers and carry, like human mules, 50 ironed shirts hanging from the balances on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at street food stalls, and it is still not possible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between 4:00 and 7:00 p.m.
It didn't seem like a crisis at all until, with all the pessimism, I decided to set up a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this assignment to cover up with a late afternoon siesta at my local JP office Morgan Chase, there were about 20 people waiting in line.
Not in front of cash windows to collect or deposit cash, but in front of the counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy's mixed goods store and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker", came for the same reason I did.
However, compared to me, they have already collected their savings from smaller banks in places they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, or Staten Island.
They collected money from so-called thrifts (a little bit like construction savings banks), money associations and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state and who claim to care for their customers as a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks went bankrupt quietly.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion worth of assets, went into bankruptcy, and when the New Yorkers came home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion worth of assets, tried to catch a bailout.
The employees of the offices and shops standing in front of me, afraid of another collapse, moved their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe harbor and that does most of the saving on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned fluently in finance over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket spoke on the phone and spoke to Lehman Borthers, the failed bank, and to her skinny senior executive, Dick Fuld, with such a familiarity, as if she were gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, a uniformed 50-year-old landlord of my tenement, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation - Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, "I have my savings in money market funds now.
I moved it, I won't take any chances."
Muslim graves desecrated after the Austrian right-wing break
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, from the Austrian right-wing party of the Free and Filip Dewinter from the Belgian right-wing party Vlaams Belang participates in the demonstration which presented in Antwerp on Thursday 17 January 2008 to the organization "City against Islamization".
They carry signs similar to traffic signs that show mosques crossed out by the red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating the Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend in which extreme right-wing parties made huge profits in general elections.
Over 90 graves in the cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were badly damaged between Friday evening and this morning and the police believe it was an organized event.
The culprits sprayed Jewish symbols on some graves, such as the star of David, but the detectives believe that this may have been an attempt to mask the motives of extremists led by hatred toward Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether this incident was linked in any way to the elections.
A spokesman for the Islamic community here said that they are "deeply shocked" by reports of desecration coming as the Muslim Lent Moon of Ramadan approaches the end.
Meanwhile, Austria enters the round of finding its own soul after the right swings in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
Both far-right parties, which gained more than 30 percent of the votes, the Free Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, waged a vehemently anti-immigration campaign, and some of their slogans were condemned as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the Free Party, who won over 18 percent of the votes, protested against scarves and burkas in the campaign, and even expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived as related to Islam.
At the last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets and argue that these are political symbols of the ongoing Islamisation of Austria and Europe.
The polls and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which put the extreme right in place of the country's strongest political bloc, indicate that this change was mainly caused by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
