"To capture the true character, I take pictures of the master outside the scene." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no calls, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great flamenco masters, freed from focusing on interpretation - I will only achieve the relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
An artist on one side.
On the other hand, human.
Inseparable, aside from privacy, in those moments away from the audience - then you can see the intimate gesture, depth of the glimpse or passionate gesture of hands that are carefree because they are not going to step on stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" theatrics of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with that less-known face of masters.
With this intention, the photographer builds a unique iconography of flamenco from various backgrounds.
The exhibition, which takes place within the framework of the Moon of Flamenco Photography (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca), "reflects the ever-growing international significance of flamenco", says the author and explains that "Flamenco-people" "may be any kind of people, but when you look at photographs, you will find that they are not typical pictures of artists on the scene.
These people portraited "on the street" are artists capable of bringing passion, sadness, joy to the scene... and completely captivating the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
He wears his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco giants.
Enchanted by the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey of portraiting flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a board camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble a classic photograph.
The application of different stylistic means is contrary to the classical base of the image and lends it the present spirit, an idea that Bauer himself thinks is mirrored by flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, which, however, continues to surprise and evolve."
What tears down the audience is not the action of dance, singing or play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we meet the most important, the spirit that appears in the way of perception, being and experiencing, that was and is the constant of the work presented during these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
This selection of almost 70 photographers creates famous flamenco characters such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project became a kind of flamenco anthology and will soon see a book edition that will contain exhibited portraits.
The passion for portraitry led Bauer to the idea of repeating the idea of a "Portraits of a Sports Veteran" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept of "Flamenco-people" is different, the photographer admits that "picture people, get to know them and have the opportunity for a moment, whether longer or just short, to enter their lives - that is my passion.
I think in the photograph, the portrait is the most difficult genre.
One encounters or encounters people, personalities who sometimes don't even know, or give them only a few minutes to take pictures.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas."
The collection of portraits of the contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is exhibited in the Gallery El Fotómata in the street de la Mata 20, parallel to Alameda de Hercules, and can be visited until 16 October.
Vargas Llosa admits that the novel he's writing is "trouble."
It takes place in an environment that is not yet known and tells of events unknown to it, yet Mario Vargas Llosa intends to successfully implement his new project - he is currently working on a novel whose main hero is Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who lived in the Congo for 20 years and traveled even in the Amazon.
