Interview - Blood that is sure again
Yesterday Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the foundation, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced because Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state reserve of blood administered by the Canadian Red Cross transfusion department was contaminated by the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the wave of displeasure in the public, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Kráter, to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krhter was delaying his report, some provinces set in motion a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this role was played by the Gélinea Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krhter report, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Hema-Québec, who was to manage Quebec, and the Canadian blood company for supplying all provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Québec began his activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system," recalls Dr.
"The situation was depressing.
By a consistent effort to increase the safety of blood products and by constant work in this area over the coming years, we have regained the public's confidence," Hema-Québek said, proudly adding that almost 94% of the Québek population had already trusted in early 2008.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"At that time we saw many cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the basic recommendations of Krhter and Gélineau's report, according to which, if we do not know and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures must be taken.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who have stayed in the United Kingdom since 1980 for more than one month.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the principle of prudence."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique was found on the market to detect the HIV virus: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that directly reveal the presence of the virus itself in donor blood, and not the presence of antibodies based on tests previously used.
The NAT tests have enabled the deaf period to be shortened between the moment of the patient’s infection and the moment when our techniques in the blood may reveal the first viruses, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing about it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood is now exposed to one out of 12 million people.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone gets HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through blood products to occur.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary for recovery," says Hema-Québek, head of management.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of disease element can appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like West Nile, is transmitted to blood by insect stings.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," Dr. Décary continues, stressing that, in addition to the safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supplies.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment for cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% of Québečans allowed to donate."
Any healthy person at least 18 years of age, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that's six times a year.
On average, 14% of blood - supplyers are not accepted because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud fevers are rampant, they are excluded for one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, donors’ networks need to be supplemented in proportion to their ageing and no longer able to donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to give blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to give blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québek, who also manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, is flowing with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand blood samples from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we expect to collect over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
