Operation to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the biggest bailout economic plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the plan, using $700 billion to slow the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months, must still be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms ensuring the payment of public money deposited, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to non-payment, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
US Finance Minister Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday minutes after midnight, after the end of the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and we have reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis currently taking place on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we do not do this, the trauma, the chaos and the disruption of American daily life will be huge," said Republican Judd Gregg.
During the last hours, negotiations have started at the maximum speed of fear of the effect that another failure would have on investors’ mood.
The time limit was to open the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US President were invited to negotiate later and both expressed themselves rather in favour of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added to the agreement some measures, in particular the aim of enabling owners to maintain their residence, and the wage of the heads of the state-saved companies.
"When we ask the taxpayers to take special measures for some people's irresponsibility, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on television.
His Republican opponent John McCain, who was asked by another station to vote in favour of the proposed plan, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I've read, [shows] that it's something that we'll all have to spend and that we can move on with.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The objective of the 700-billion-dollar plan is to buy doubtful claims and risk and unsaleable assets from US financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by the bursting bubble in the real estate market, which first led to the collapse of risk mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the decomposition of banks and financial institutions.
The failure of last week's first draft agreement was caused by Republican MPs.
Since the Democrats agreed that the government would only guarantee some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty, but not buy them, there is a belief that the impasse is averted.
In an effort to bring the conflicting views closer together in Congress, a measure was added that the government would be able to introduce new charges to help it regain its contribution if, as a result of the programme, it had to take over losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which it will be possible to add an additional 100 billion if the President considers it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in saved companies, which, in the event of profits, will pay him dividends and which he will be able to sell again when this is over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the property seizure procedures related to the loans to which the plan relates, as well as to set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The planners of the plan would like to put him to the vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain that their plan will be green.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project in both Republican and democratic camps.
"It is quite obvious that Washington can't hear you," declared Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's financial committee, to the electorate.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
However, profiting on taxpayers is not the answer."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed "the Skeptic Committee", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"The four hundred respected professors of economics, among them three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too quickly and carefully examine which path to take," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
At the end of the emergency meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for EUR 11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French Bank of BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from buying its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost EUR 2 billion ($2.9 billion) as a result of a crisis of risk loans to buy real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people, among the 20 largest European banks and among the ten largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money," said the Dutch finance minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
This is what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times."
On the other side of the Channel, so far, the British government seems to have launched the nationalisation of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion ($75,5 billion) constituted loans to buy real estate.
According to yesterday's announcement, the Spanish bank Santander will buy out the branches and accounts of British bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government has had to nationalize since the start of the financial crisis.
