Smart car imitates bumblebee flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
Bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the Japanese trade fair CEATEC, was inspired by engineers from Nissan bumblebees. It was about how to build a new generation of systems preventing collisions.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan designed a biomimetic robotic control system of BR23C type, a robotized minicar equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our protective packaging," he explained at Kazuhiro Doi exhibition, the CEO of the brand for technological PR and research and development.
Composite eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see more than 300 degrees in all directions of view.
Engineers reached the idea of the laser distance meter to copy the function of the composite eye.
It identifies the obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters in front of the BR23C in the 180-degree field of vision, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car starts imitating the movements of the bee and turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver is taking place in an entirely instinctive way.
"If that were not the case, a robotic car would not be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective packaging within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not last longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer accumulators that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, an instinctive, intelligent response, not a processing ability, is important, the less data storage.
This mechanism must only process and respond to several incoming signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, therefore he constantly uses only memory of the size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with a giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing an immediate avoidance technology that, according to Nissan's estimate, could reach serial-produced vehicles within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles.
