Both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain also supported the compromise on the package.
Minister of Finance Henry Paulson said about the outcome of the compromise: "The programme will work and it will be effective, but further action needs to be taken."
The written form of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. in Washington time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but did not cause any special rise on the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will first vote on the draft legal standard, which will be heard in the name of the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act, which is to be established by the Programme, and then it will be the Senate's turn.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, then the news of the agreement was also welcomed at the White House.
"We are satisfied with the progress made last night and appreciate both sides' efforts to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said spokesperson Tony Fratto.
After all, the program differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal, which was intended to ensure that a total of $700 billion was spent on the purchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of half of $700 billion in the first round, so that 250 billion will be used immediately after Congress is expected to decide on the matter on Monday, and the Treasury will buy mortgage-backed securities, which are rated as unquality, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will depend on the President's decision.
The programme will be controlled by a special congregation, the chairman of which will also be a member of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Spending the other half of $700 billion will depend on Congress's next decision.
The Ministry of Finance can apply a combined policy within the meaning of the law: it can simultaneously buy off low-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other "poisoned" loans.
The purchase may take place within auctions directly, and the competent representatives of the Ministry have informed them.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance grants them guarantees for a means of providing cause for concern, for which the company will then pay the price corresponding to the amount of damage expected.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to meet the urgent requirements of the US financial system, whether it is a large purchase of bad funds, their insurance, or the prevention of systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the large money institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, bank bosses who are in trouble waiting to help the state can count on the government to cut their severance pay - which is simply called a "golden parachute" in overseas slang.
Only in certain cases will they be reduced, and these restrictions will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction basically means that if the Ministry buys in the auction, a tax mark will be imposed on the gold parachutes if the fallen bank directors are not sent straight to retirement.
In the event of a direct buy-back of low-quality loans, the government will aggressively intervene in order to ensure that money is not excessive for management.
It must be added that the already existing gold-falling contracts will not change, the restriction concerns only new ones, which is intended to further stimulate participation in the programme.
"This is the first case in American history to have legal restrictions on the remuneration of CEOs in force," commented Chairman of the Committee on Financial Services of the House of Representatives, Democrat Barney Frank.
Moreover, the state in the banks participating in the programme will be entitled to a share, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, because once the economy and the rescued bank are on their feet, they can also make a profit from the transaction.
The proposal contains that in the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be repaid to taxpayers.
Of course, there have also been voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
"This is not what the American citizens asked us to do, because this does not protect taxpayers' dollars," said the Republican Congressman from California Darrell Issa.
His democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes that the adoption of the provisions was urged by exactly those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 due to the previous month, then by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office announced.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1,1 percent higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent year-on-year.
Production prices in the industry were 0.7 percent higher as a result of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, rising by 3.2 percent year on year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by at least 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing industry also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest price increase took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to the monthly increase in prices in the luggage and saddlery products sector by 4.6 percent, respectively, footwear production by 2.5 percent.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical materials and products sector (1.6 percent).
Prices decreased in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other manufacturing sectors, we measured price increases in the range 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sector, which has a large weight in the domestic sales of the industry, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly by the continued effect of the officially established increase in gas prices since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison of domestic sales in each processing industry, prices increased most in the oil processing industry (32.4 percent).
In the manufacturing sector, 13,2 % could be observed, in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products with a decisive weight, then 11 % price increase.
Prices decreased in the textile and textile industries (2.5 percent) and electrical machinery (0.3 percent).
In other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2 percent during the last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water industries exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7 percent.
From the point of view of the sector's focus, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the material asset sector was shown on domestic sales in August.
In consumer goods industries, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in energy processing and further processing sectors, prices did not change in relation to the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increase in respect of the same month of the previous year was observed in energy from processing and further processing sectors (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods sector, we measured an increase in prices of 6.8 percent, while in the case of tangible assets, prices fell by 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, with a decrease of 3.9 percent in the 12-month comparison.
In one month, our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent relative to the euro, then by 7.1 percent relative to the dollar, increased by 7.5 percent relative to the euro compared to August 2007 and by 15.9 percent relative to the dollar.
